    <h1>About</h1>
    Capperucci et al. explored how mentoring and peer support can help teachers grow professionally and improve schools overall. They developed guidelines as part of the RESPOND European Erasmus+ project to clarify how different people in schools, like mentors and colleagues, can support teachers. Mentors provide formal support, while peers offer informal help. These guidelines aim to show how these relationships can work together to benefit teachers and schools. This study matters because it highlights the importance of both structured and casual support systems in helping teachers develop their skills, which can lead to better teaching and a stronger school community.
  </article>
  <article id="keywords-article-IJNF3LSR" class="keywords-article">
    <h1>Keywords</h1>
    Mentoring, Peer-to-Peer Support, Teacher Professional Development, School Development, Erasmus+ Project
  </article>
  <article id="abstract-article-IJNF3LSR" class="abstract-article">
    <h1>Scientific abstract</h1>
    This paper presents a part of the RESPOND European Erasmus+-project on the  
mutually sustaining relationship between teacher professional development and overall school  
development. The focus is on one of four product results from the project, “The RESPOND Teacher  
Professional Development Support Guidelines” developed as a tool for understanding the roles of  
and interactions between different actors in school, with particular reference to the role of  
mentors for formal institutional support and peer-to-peer support for informal support between  
colleagues. The paper concludes with a reflection on the aims and the intended impact of the  
guidelines.
  </article>
